entry.title: Designing and Creating a Database
entry.summary: Baseball is a great topic to practice skills in data science. Because of the long history within baseball of the collection and analysis of statistics (most famously Sabermetrics featured in the movie Moneyball), there is a massive potential of answering a pletheora of questions regarding baseball. We will be working with a file of Major League Baseball games from Retrosheet. Retrosheet compiles detailed statistics on baseball games from the 1800s through today. With such a massive amount of data, it will be an ideal project to design and create a relational database which could store and retreive these data efficiently.

<h2 id="-1.-Introduction"><a name="1" /> 1. Introduction<a class="anchor-link" href="#-1.-Introduction">¶</a></h2><hr>
<p>Baseball is a great topic to practice skills in data science. Because of the long history within baseball of the collection and analysis of statistics (most famously <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabermetrics">Sabermetrics</a> featured in the movie <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moneyball_%28film%29">Moneyball</a>), there is a massive potential of answering a pletheora of questions regarding baseball.</p>
<h4 id="Note-on-the-data">Note on the data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Note-on-the-data">¶</a></h4><p>We will be working with a file of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_League_Baseball">Major League Baseball</a> games from <a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/gamelogs/index.html">Retrosheet</a>. Retrosheet compiles detailed statistics on baseball games from the 1800s through today. With such a massive amount of data, it will be an ideal project to design and create a relational database which could store and retreive these data efficiently.</p>
<h4 id="CSV-files-in-this-projects:">CSV files in this projects:<a class="anchor-link" href="#CSV-files-in-this-projects:">¶</a></h4><ul>
<li><code>game_log.csv</code> has been produced by combining 127 CSV files from retrosheet (pre-cleaned)</li>
<li><code>park_codes.csv</code> list of ballpark IDs and addresses</li>
<li><code>person_codes.csv</code> list of baseball player IDs and names</li>
<li><code>team_codes.csv</code> list of team IDs and associated leagues</li>
<li><code>game_log_fields.csv</code> a helper file which will only function as a lookup guidance.</li>
<li><code>appearance_type.csv</code> contains data that have been manually entered to fill a table in SQLite later</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<h4 id="The-gloal-of-this-project:">The gloal of this project:<a class="anchor-link" href="#The-gloal-of-this-project:">¶</a></h4><ul>
<li>Utilize <strong><em>SQLite</em></strong> as our databse</li>
<li>Execute SQL in python library <strong><em>sqlite3</em></strong></li>
<li>Design a <strong><em>normalized</em></strong> database schema</li>
<li>Create <strong><em>normalized</em></strong> tables for our database</li>
<li>Insert data into our normalized tables</li>
</ul>
<p>Let's start by running the <code>game_log_fields.txt</code> to create a lookup reference in this notebook for the fields in the game_log data.</p>

<p>Now that we have imported the last 3 CSV files, we can observe that the largest of these 3 are not surpringly the <code>person_codes</code>. Most the the column names are intuitive to decipher, yet a few columns might require a minor clarification, such as the <code>league</code> column.</p>

<h2 id="-3.-Importing-Data-into-SQLite"><a name="3" /> 3. Importing Data into SQLite<a class="anchor-link" href="#-3.-Importing-Data-into-SQLite">¶</a></h2><p>To insert data into a <strong><em>normalized database</em></strong>, we'll need a single column that can be used as a <code>primary key</code>. The game log file does not have a single column that can be used as a primary key to uniquely identify each game. Fortunately, if we explore the Retrosheet site, we can find this <a href="https://www.retrosheet.org/eventfile.htm">data dictionary</a> for their event files, which list every event within each game. This includes the following description:</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>id:</strong> Each game begins with a twelve character ID record which identifies the date, home team, and number of the game. For example, <code>ATL198304080</code> should be read as follows. The <strong>first three</strong> characters identify the home team (the Braves). The <strong>next four</strong> are the year (1983). The <strong>next two</strong> are the month (April) using the standard numeric notation, 04, <strong>followed by the day</strong> (08). The <strong>last digit</strong> indicates if this is a single game (0), first game (1) or second game (2) if more than one game is played during a day, usually a double header The id record starts the description of a game thus ending the description of the preceding game in the file.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now that we know how to assemble the primary key, we will first import the dataframes into individual temporary tables in the SQLite database. Hereafter, we will create a primary key column in the game_log table.</p>
<p>We will handle all data transfers by using <code>sqlite3</code> and <code>DataFrame.to_sql()</code>. In this quest we will create 2 functions which will become very convinient. The first funciton will be <code>run_query</code> which will be used for retreiving data from the SQLite database. The second function will be <code>run_command</code> which will be used to run SQL that only modify the database itself.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [10]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">sqlite3</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib</span>
<span class="o">%</span><span class="k">matplotlib</span> inline

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">run_query</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">q</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">with</span> <span class="n">sqlite3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">connect</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Data/database/mlb.db'</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_sql</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">run_command</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">q</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="k">with</span> <span class="n">sqlite3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">connect</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Data/database/mlb.db'</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">:</span>
        <span class="n">conn</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">execute</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'PRAGMA foreign_keys = ON;'</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># enforcement of foreign key restraints</span>
        <span class="n">conn</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">isolation_level</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="kc">None</span>
        <span class="n">conn</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">execute</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">q</span><span class="p">)</span>
        <span class="k">return</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The 2 functions are now ready to make our life easier. The next step is to transfer all our data from the dataframes to the  SQLite database by using <code>DataFrame.to_sql()</code>. Since no SQLite database exists at this time, the <code>DataFrame.to_sql()</code> will automatically create one for us.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [11]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">warnings</span>
<span class="n">warnings</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">filterwarnings</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'ignore'</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># ignores irrelevant warnings</span>

<span class="n">conn</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">sqlite3</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">connect</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Data/database/mlb.db'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">team_codes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_sql</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'team_codes'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># the index=False will ensure no index column will be created</span>
<span class="n">park_codes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_sql</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'park_codes'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">person_codes</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_sql</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'person_codes'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">game_log</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_sql</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'game_log'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">conn</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">conn</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">close</span><span class="p">()</span> <span class="c1"># closes the connection with the SQLite database</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Our SQLite database now have 4 tables with data. We will perform this task with the <code>run_command</code> function to carry out the <code>SQL</code> commands.</p>

<h2 id="-4.-Designing-and-Creating-a-Normalized-Database"><a name="4" /> 4. Designing and Creating a Normalized Database<a class="anchor-link" href="#-4.-Designing-and-Creating-a-Normalized-Database">¶</a></h2><p>The next step is to design a normalized database which will contain all the data. For this task I have used <a href="https://www.dbdesigner.net">DbDesigner.net</a> to to create the schema below:</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64, " alt="database_diagram.png"></p>
<p>By refering to this schema, I will walk through the rational behind the <strong><em>particular choices</em></strong>. We will start by creating the tables that do not contain any <code>foreign key</code> relations. It is important to start with these tables, as other tables will have relations to these tables, and so these tables will need to exist first.</p>
<p>The tables we will create are below, with some notes on the normalization choices made:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>person</code><ul>
<li>Each of the 'debut' columns have been omitted, as these dates will be able to be extracted from the data in other tables.</li>
<li>Since the game log file has no data on coaches, I made the decision to not include this data.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><code>park</code><ul>
<li>Again, the start, end, and league columns contain data which can be elucidated by data found in the main game log and can be removed.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><code>league</code><ul>
<li>Because some of the older leagues are not well known, we will create a table to store league names.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><code>appearance_type</code><ul>
<li>Our appearance table will include data on players with positions, umpires, managers, and awards (like winning pitcher). This table will store information on what different types of appearances are available.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Before we move on with the explanation of the normalization process in the database schema, let's <strong><em>create these 4 tables</em></strong> and insert the correct data.</p>

<h3 id="-4.1-Adding-the-Team-and-Game-Tables"><a name="4.1" /> 4.1 Adding the Team and Game Tables<a class="anchor-link" href="#-4.1-Adding-the-Team-and-Game-Tables">¶</a></h3><p>Now that we have added all of the tables that don't have foreign key relationships, lets add the next two tables. The <code>game</code> and <code>team</code> tables need to exist before our two appearance tables are created.</p>
<p>Here are some notes on the normalization choices made with each of these tables:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>team</code><ul>
<li>The <strong><em>start</em></strong>, <strong><em>end</em></strong>, and <strong><em>sequence</em></strong> columns can be derived from the game level data.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><code>game</code><ul>
<li>I have chosen to include all columns for the game log that don't refer to one specific team or player, instead putting those in two appearance tables.</li>
<li>I have removed the column with the <strong><em>day of the week</em></strong>, as this can be derived from the date.</li>
<li>I have changed the day_night column to <strong><em>day</em></strong>, with the intention of making this a <code>boolean</code> column. Even though SQLite doesn't support the boolean type, we can use this when creating our table and SQLite will manage the underlying types behind the scenes. This means that anyone quering the schema of our database in the future understands how that column is intended to be used.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<h3 id="-4.2-Adding-the-Team-Appearance-Table"><a name="4.2" /> 4.2 Adding the Team Appearance Table<a class="anchor-link" href="#-4.2-Adding-the-Team-Appearance-Table">¶</a></h3><p>The <code>team_appearance</code> table has a <code>compound primary</code> key composed of the team name and the game ID. In addition, a <code>boolean</code> column <code>home</code> is used to differentiate between the home and the away team. The rest of the columns are scores or statistics that in our original game log are repeated for each of the home and away teams.
In order to insert this data cleanly, we'll need to use a <code>UNION</code> clause</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<h3 id="-4.3-Adding-the-Person-Appearance-Table"><a name="4.3" /> 4.3 Adding the Person Appearance Table<a class="anchor-link" href="#-4.3-Adding-the-Person-Appearance-Table">¶</a></h3><p>The final table we need to create is <code>person_appearance</code>. The table will be used to store information on appearances in games by <strong><em>managers</em></strong>, <strong><em>players</em></strong>, and <strong><em>umpires</em></strong> as detailed in the <code>appearance_type table</code>.</p>
<p>We can fill the <code>person_appearance</code> with data from the <code>game_log</code> table by selecting the different columns that refer to either <strong><em>managers</em></strong>, <strong><em>players</em></strong> or <strong><em>umpires</em></strong>, and subsequently append them by using the <code>UNION</code> clause.</p>
<p>We will fill the <code>person_appearance</code> in 2 step. In the first step we will insert all data related to anything but the offensive and defensive positions:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [20]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">q</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'''</span>
<span class="s1">CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS person_appearance (</span>
<span class="s1">    appearance_id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,</span>
<span class="s1">    person_id VARCHAR(10),</span>
<span class="s1">    team_id VARCHAR(3),</span>
<span class="s1">    game_id VARCHAR(10),</span>
<span class="s1">    appearance_type_id INTEGER,</span>
<span class="s1">        FOREIGN KEY (person_id) REFERENCES person(person_id) ON UPDATE CASCADE ON DELETE SET NULL</span>
<span class="s1">        FOREIGN KEY (team_id) REFERENCES team(team_id) ON UPDATE CASCADE ON DELETE SET NULL</span>
<span class="s1">        FOREIGN KEY (game_id) REFERENCES game(game_id) ON UPDATE CASCADE ON DELETE SET NULL</span>
<span class="s1">        FOREIGN KEY (appearance_type_id) REFERENCES appearance_type(appearance_type_id) ON UPDATE CASCADE ON DELETE SET NULL  </span>
<span class="s1">)</span>
<span class="s1">'''</span>
